<OperationProcedure>
<Para>Passenger oxygen requirements vary with the cruise altitude, the cabin pressure altitude to which an airplane may descend in the event of a depressurization during the flight, and the time required to make the emergency descent.  If the airplane is operated at FL 250 or below and is able to descend to 14,000 feet cabin pressure altitude or below within four minutes following
depressurization, oxygen must be available for 10% of passenger cabin occupants for 30 minutes. </Para>
<Para>If the airplane is operated at or below FL 250 and is unable to descend to 14,000 or below within four minutes, or if the airplane is operated above FL 250 regardless of the time to descend to 14,000 feet cabin pressure altitude or below following depressurization, oxygen must be available for 10% of the passenger cabin occupants for the duration of the flight with cabin
pressure altitudes above 10,000 feet and at or below 14,000 feet, except that there must not be less than a 10-minute supply for the passenger cabin occupants.</Para>
<Para>If the airplane is able to descend to between 14,000 and 15,000 feet cabin pressure altitude, sufficient oxygen must be available for 30% of passenger cabin occupants.  If the airplane cannot descend below 15,000 feet cabin pressure altitude, oxygen must be available for all (100%) of the passenger cabin occupants.  In these cases, oxygen must be available for the required
number of passengers for the entire duration of the flight  flown at the cabin pressure altitudes above 14,000 feet.  In all cases, sufficient oxygen must be available for the required number of passengers for at least 10 minutes.</Para>
<Para>For flights above flight level 250, an undiluted oxygen supply is required for no less than two percent of the passengers for that portion of the flight at cabin pressure altitudes above 8,000 feet following depressurization.  In no case will the supply be less than that required for one person.</Para>
